\par\plain {Beksinski - [B\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u603\'3Fk\u712\'27\u597\'3Fi\u626\'3Fski] - (Bek-shen-ski)}
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {I.I}
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {December 12, 2102}
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {Mission Commander Oya Bereket\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s voice came in through The Experiment\u8217\'92s intercom, calling  Moto Owusu to attention. }
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Moto, let\u8217\'92s -uh- complete this.\u8221\'94  The peculiarities of Oya\u8217\'92s accent were hard for Moto to nail down. She was the only native Turk he\u8217\'92d ever met, and to his unlearned ear she sounded Russian. Oya had forgiven him when he\u8217\'92d drawn the comparison. }
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m ready.\u8221\'94 Moto replied, stowing his pad and pen. It was finally time.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93And Alberto?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Omnipresent,\u8221\'94 came Alberto\u8217\'92s voice, the kind of voice that was always smiling.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93O.K. Let\u8217\'92s get this over with.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {For the next three hours, system statuses and observations were read out, a final redundancy meant to focus the crew. Moto knew it was an unnecessary procedure because he knew that he, Oya, and Alberto had each dreamed of this moment a thousand times over, and they had each run through the simulations a thousand times more. Still, he kept a little motivating fear around in  his thoughts to keep him sharp, because while the mission of The Experiment was worth dying for, absent-minded mistakes were not. Even after this final systems check wrapped up, and the three settled into The Experiment\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s central command module, Moto kept on considering the many manners in which he might die during the next half-hour. Oya was the last to float in.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Everyone tucked in?\u8221\'94, she asked.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I was waiting for you,\u8221\'94 Alberto said gruffly, scratching his unkempt beard in a  serious attempt to appear nonchalant. \u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s, uh, just not the same if I do it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Alberto, this ship has just three hundred cubic meters of space and I\u8217\'92m sure I\u8217\'92ve not even touched you.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes, you have.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If I did it wasn\u8217\'92t on purpose.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, then -\u8221\'94 Alberto smiled. \u8220\'93Is this not a day of firsts?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain { \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It certainly is,\u8221\'94 Oya said as she promptly planted her foot on Alberto\u8217\'92s head, and used it as a stepping stone to float her up to her console on the ceiling. That was her least favorite quirk of The Experiment\u8217\'92s design, that the easiest way to get to her seat involved bothering Alberto. Everything else she loved, most of all she loved that this command capsule was capped by a large, glass hemisphere. In functional terms it was completely unnecessary -  they would never have need to pilot the ship by sight - but it offered a grand view the Earth from 375 km up. At the moment the planet was shifting just out of frame, but she could still make out the Atlantic Ocean with its magnificent phytoplankton blooms, thousands of miles long, glowing prussian-blue in whirling ocean gyres. }
\par\plain { Moto did not care much for the Earth. His eyes sought out Alpha Pyxidis, the brightest star of a faint constellation. It was their destination. He finally found it when The Experiment halted it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s reorientation, not because he could see it, but because he knew it *must* be straight ahead in the most absolute sense. Their navigational calculations *must* be right, otherwise, if the ship\u8217\'92s tunneling was off by just a tenth of a degree, they might impact the core of some hidden planetoid, or it might tumble into the event horizon of a rogue black hole - just a few possibilities in the infinite class of cosmic deaths.}
\par\plain { Alberto rarely cared to look outside, but he appreciated the way in which this window gave The Experiment\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s hodgepodge structure a sense of direction. It was the only  human element amongst the jumble of chalk-white spheres and cylinders. In all he thought it was an ugly, utilitarian design so typical of space-built craft. He especially hated the way the two enormous  space warping rings orbited The Expirment\u8217\'92s nucleus of capsules - it made the whole thing look like a tumorous atom, an icon of warped and degenerate science - lacking in the elegance that signified a deep and complete understanding of the physics.  }
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, we\u8217\'92ve prepared as best we can,\u8221\'94 Alberto said. He looked up at Oya with an anxious grin, expecting to be chastised for not being more serious, but Oya didn\u8217\'92t do or say anything.  \u8220\'93Oya,\u8221\'94 he continued, \u8220\'93 it\u8217\'92s not like what we do in the next ten minutes is going to affect anything. We\u8217\'92ve been working for years, and-\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {Alberto paused when he caught the reflection of Oya\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes rolling back in annoyance.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Eh, Oya? Maybe at this point we should say, \u8216\'91No worries\u8217\'92.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No worries for you Alberto, means more worries for me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ohhhh, Magn\u237\'EDfico.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Do not start.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Fingertips to lips. Kiss. Explode.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What?\u8221\'94 Oya asked, finally looking down at him through a little space in between her chair and console.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Try it. Like this.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain { Alberto closed his eyes and knitted his brows together, and blew a chef\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s kiss out towards Oya. In case this wasn\u8217\'92t enough, his bearded jaw swung sigh-smiling in faked orgasmic pleasure. }
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What is wrong with you?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I just enjoy your way of saying simple things simply.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s amazing that this needs to be said,\u8221\'94 Moto interjected, \u8220\'93but we are here to solve problems, not create them.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh, that was good too!\u8221\'94 Alberto exclaimed as he pretended to take Moto\u8217\'92s admonishment to heart, muttering aloud, \u8220\'93Solve problems, not create them. Very good.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Let\u8217\'92s try this again. Strap in.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {Two green lights lit up on the panel in front Alberto, and he was forced to focus. He signaled Moto to check off a few redundant switches, in preparation for takeoff.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Are we ready?\u8221\'94 Oya asked. She waited for both Moto and Alberto to respond in the affirmative, then touched her headset to reach Lunar Command, and asked them how it all looked.}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You are still clear to proceed.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Beautiful,\u8221\'94 she said.}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We\u8217\'92ll be waiting for your return in twenty-two hours. Good luck.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Whenever you\u8217\'92re ready, Moto.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Just another dry run,\u8221\'94 Moto said silently, pausing to appreciate the little details - like the rough, noisy texture of the red plastic switch under his thumb, the slight tinge of freon in the air, and the low-background hum of the electric discombobulator. His eyes focused on the digital readout of the onboard atomic clock, synced with Earth\u8217\'92s, and he was able to pinpoint the exact moment, down to 1/100th of a second, that he flipped the switch and became the first human to warp space-time around human cargo: 6:21:244 hours, GMT, on December 12, 2154.}
\par\plain {The arms that connected the Experiment's nucleus to its outer rings detached, and then the two rings began to spin, one forward on pitch , the other sidewise on yaw. Each time they passed over the ship\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s forward vector they seemed to strike - like flint against steel - spewing out a blue spark of plasma. In the absence of sound, Moto\u8217\'92s brain invented an electric \u8216\'91zap\u8217\'92 to accompany the bright collision of particles out in front, and a low frequency \u8216\'91whump-thump\u8217\'92 to the heavy rings as they revolved around the rest of the structure. }
\par\plain {The first rotational period took a full 14 seconds, according to Moto\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s hand count. }
\par\plain {The second period, 7 seconds. }
\par\plain {Space began to fold around them, and the whole structure moved forward, imperceptibly at first, but soon enough the stars at the sides began to stretch, and the plasma out in front sputtered into a steady flame. Beyond this point Moto was not able to construct a coherent sequence of events.}
\par\plain {To outside observers, the Experiment\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s movement looked strange - the ship\u8217\'92s translation over time adhered to a curve which only appeared in abstract mathematics. It was an unnatural function, with no elegant smoothing in and out, no sense of natural timing that one normally associates with Newtonian physics. It was like the ship was being summoned  into the depths of the cosmos by some capricious deity who liked to play with his food before he ate it.}
\par\plain {Inside the crew could sense movement, somehow, yet there was no inertial velocity, no fixed reference points to judge progress, as almost immediately stars faded into the dark. Oya, Moto, and Alberto just floated there in their harnesses, measuring out light years per second.}
\par\plain {As the Experiment folded the fabric of the universe around itself in greater and greater bolts, the bright plasma spread out into a bubble around the ship. As it stretched, its hot blue color shifted through to purple, then settled into a deep, suffocating red. As this light flooded into the command module it bounced around the interior with an intensity that seemed to ignite the controlled atmosphere of the cabin, the red light seemingly taking on substance, adhering to surfaces. Edges seemed to merge into each other, and soon Moto could not distinguish between interior and exterior. He tried to hold focus by reading out the distance measurements from his console, committing them to memory - but the apparent melting of the display just magnified the sensation of his mind\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s disassembly. Dark, shifting patterns raced over the contours of the cabin\u8217\'92s interior, a mesmerizing effect, and Moto entered into a familiar psychedelic trance in which static and moving things merged into a third state, the ___ in which the artificial construction of reality that occurs within the brain begins to atrophy. Moto just sat there like a newborn, wide-eyed, a sense-organ with no thought..}
\par\plain {Eventually it all began to dim, and the plasma began to dissipate, taking with it the deep crimson light that had consumed the crew. Moto began to sense the rigidity of the outer rings again, and this in turn resolved that familiar \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91whump-thump\u8217\'92 of their passing overhead, and to this Moto was able to reorient his sensibilities. The ship was quickly scaling back down the hyperbolic curve from which it had come.}
\par\plain {It took another moment still for it to come to a complete stop, and for Moto to begin to coax his rational mind back out of its shell. He could see that Alberto was still lost in rapture, while Oya had already regained her faculties and was busy doing\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 something. Moto\u8217\'92s eyes turned back out to the spatial void, stumbling over a dark planet which nearly filled the frame. It shocked him to see it, because it was very large, and very close, and it had somehow escaped his notice despite him staring at it just before. It was even silhouetted by a distant sun, which burned white, young, and beautifully.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s not our star.\u8221\'94 said Oya.}
\par\plain {She was magnificently unaffected by the experience. None of what had just happened was supposed to happen, or at least, predicted to happen. Only Alberto, who was just now rising out of his reverie, seemed to share Moto\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s bewilderment as he stared up and out to the top left-corner of the glass  dome, just off the edge of the port-side capsule. Moto followed his gaze, and there, not one hundred meters away, hanging in the blackness, was an enormous metal cylinder. As it moved into the light that reflected off the ship, he could make out letters clearly emblazoned on its side, and they read: BEKSINSKI - Mk. IV.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oya.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s one of Bekinski\u8217\'92s probes.\u8221\'94 Moto extended his arm to point to it, but Oya seemed unconcerned.}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Alberto, put us into orbit,\u8221\'94 she commanded. \u8220\'93And Moto, figure out where the hell we are.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab It took effort just for Moto to mumble, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Okay,\u8221\'94 though it didn\u8217\'92t take any effort at all to carry out the task, for The Experiment was already providing him with enough contextual information to cross reference their current position with supposed locations of Beksinski\u8217\'92s original space-bending probes. The famous engineer had sent out thousands of them to test his original version of the fabled warp drive. Galaxy type, matter distribution, and even a few identifiable neighbor galaxies provided clues as to where they were. }
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So, we are in NGC 4452.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93In the Virgo cluster.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I think.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You think?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Something is wrong with the SSU, so I can\u8217\'92t verify it. But, that\u8217\'92s probably it. I mean fuck, the universe is big.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab It was slightly off from the frequency he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d heard just before they\u8217\'92d taken off, yet, it wasn\u8217\'92t enough to distract him from the realization of the alien planet below. There the sun\u8217\'92s glancing rays lit up a thin blue horizon, curved and hazy, suggesting an atmosphere not unlike the Earth\u8217\'92s. Flecks of white clouds dotted that illuminated rim, the vanguard of a stormy weather system that might cover half a continent, though in the shadow of the planet, no land could be seen.  }
\par\plain {\tab We should name it Anatolia, Moto thought. A bone for the commander. }
\par\plain {Moto looked up at Oya, about to make the suggestion, when he saw that her head was curiously tilted to the side, listening with intent, her eyes searching the walls, wearing an expression of panic. }
\par\plain {Then it came, a worrisome rumble that echoed through the cabin, barely audible.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You hear that?\u8221\'94 Moto asked.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes,\u8221\'94 Oya said calmly. \u8220\'93But it can\u8217\'92t be too serious, or else the alarm would have-\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Just then, the low, two-tone drone of the warning system kicked in. }
\par\plain {BWEEEEE-OOOOO}
\par\plain {The status lights that trimmed the glass bubble began to flash as well, and for the second time the cabin was bathed in a pulsing red light.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The hell is that!?\u8221\'94, Alberto shouted as he fumbled with his buckle.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Something with the K-pod,\u8221\'94 Oya said as she hurriedly unbuckled herself and pushed off towards the upper hatch, towards the outer observation tube, a cocoon of triple-paned fused silica which wrapped around the command capsule\u8217\'92s midsection. \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m going up to check it out.\u8221\'94 She quietly gestured towards Moto with a beckoning nod, a silent command for him to follow suit.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m coming too,\u8221\'94 Moto declared.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What about me?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Stay there.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What!? Wait!\u8221\'94 Alberto shouted, his voice cracking in fear.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh, shut up\u8230\'85\u8221\'94 Oya muttered aloud.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No it\u8217\'92s - I don\u8217\'92t think you should - \u8221\'94 but his protestation was cut short as Oya opened the hatch. Out came an unholy metal groan that shook the thin aluminium walls of the capsule, pasting grim and terrifying thoughts into Moto\u8217\'92s head. Fear shot like lightning through his spine, quickening him to act, and so he pulled himself up into the observation tube and around the bend to match Oya, who still seemed magically unaffected by the whole experience. She floated there silently, stoically, looking out towards the rear of The Experiment\u8217\'92s nucleus. What Moto saw over her shoulder shattered his final resolve.}
\par\plain {Two of the ship\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s spherical modules there had somehow flattened out and twisted in on themselves, with their aluminium skins stretching right through each other, unbroken, warped like putty into what should have been an impossible topology. Two more spheres, closer to the core, had crumpled like tinfoil, and closer still, two airlocks appeared to be bloated, ready to explode. Only those modules near the front of the nucleus appeared to be unaffected. It was as if the ship was a tube of toothpaste, and a massive extra-dimensional roller had begun to press out the ship, starting with those two modules in the rear, and working the bubbles of compressed air up towards the bow. The whole process was still in progress.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93How?\u8221\'94 Moto managed to mutter.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We don\u8217\'92t have time to talk about it,\u8221\'94 Oya said. \u8220\'93 So, here\u8217\'92s what we\u8217\'92re going to do -\u8221\'94, but before she could finish, the metal creaks turned into loud metal pops as nuts and bolts that held the bloated airlocks together began to fracture under the stress. }
\par\plain {Alberto\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s strained voice came in through the intercom: \u8220\'93We\u8217\'92re ripping apart!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Do what you can!\u8221\'94, Oya shrieked back before turning to Moto to say, \u8220\'93Something\u8217\'92s not right.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Moto actually laughed.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No.\u8221\'94 Oya continued. \u8220\'93If we missed Pyxidis then we missed Pyxidis , but the fact that we're here, same fucking place as one of Beksinski\u8217\'92s probes, and a fucking planet with liquid water and a breathable atmosphere...\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Moto wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t paying attention. He was looking out at the storage capsule, and attached to it, the last available escape pod - one that could survive through atmosphere reentry. He looked back at Oya, and noticed that she had seen it too.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Alberto?\u8221\'94 Moto asked.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Fuck him.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {The Experiment lurched as one of its forward  ion engines suddenly fired, effectively braking their movement, and the whole ship began to decelerate and  to fall into the planet. Moto and Oya hurried back down to the command module, heading for the airlock in floor that lead to the escape pod. As they passed through, Moto noticed something missing and stopped himself suddenly, causing Oya to crash into him.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Moto, what the hell!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Alberto\u8217\'92s gone.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Indeed he was. Moto looked back at Oya, and their eyes locked in shared realization: Alberto had left to take the escape pod for himself.}
\par\plain {Oya pushed past Moto and sped through the airlock, further into ship\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s imploding core, but instead of a missing pod, they stumbled upon Alberto\u8217\'92s portly, bleeding corpse floating serenely in the middle of it\u8217\'92s bloated airlock.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What the hell happened to him!?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {The answer came from a rivet in the wall. Unable to resist the forces tearing at it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s aluminum sheathing, it shot out like a bullet to stab Oya shank-side first in the stomach, with its head neatly plugging the wound. }
\par\plain {Oya recoiled with a gasp, and quickly raised her hand to stop Moto, before pointing down at the hatch on the floor.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93NO! No. Open the fucking pod!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\tab Moto moved to twist the rescue pod\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s hatch open. After a moment of struggle, he grabbed a silver hammer that was strapped to the wall, and with two swift strokes, was able to open the lid. A blast of stale air escaped the pod as the hatch swung open.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Get in\u8221\'94, she said to Moto.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You first.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Through the porthole behind Moto, Oya could see the thin atmosphere feeding a sputtering flame, licking at the window. The Experiment had begun to crumble through the planet\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s mesosphere. }
\par\plain {There was no time to argue. She ripped Moto\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s grip from the wall and pushed him into the pod. Moto bounded off the cushioned interior and back up to Oya, clearly attempting to guide her into the pod with him. }
\par\plain {Just then a loud shock signaled collision with the stratosphere, and Oya was flung against the back of the airlock. began to struggle against the inertial forces in her attempt to close the hatch. The now violent shaking caused her to bite through her tongue, bubbling blood out of her mouth and down the flared tendons of her neck. Outside a terrible fire roared and the ship began to groan madly as the tensile strength of its skeleton neared its limits. She was desperate now. The hatch was designed to be operated in zero-g and was so thick and heavy, - the added G\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s of reentry made the task herculean. Oya repositioned her body so that her back rested against the open hatch and her feet met the nearby wall. She could use more leg and glute strength from this position. She had to trust Moto. At once she began to push with all her strength. Slowly, the hatch moved. Through the blood and pain she focused on her breathing.}
