\par\plain {\tab It isn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t hard to differentiate between sleep and other states of unconsciousness, like the blackout, like the kind produced when Moto\u8217\'92s head impacted his escape pod\u8217\'92s thick aluminium plating while traveling at near terminal speeds. Sleep can be considered to be a lived experience, inasmuch as one\u8217\'92s dreams are remembered. At the very least, while sleeping, the passage of time is always tracked, or estimated, via a vigilant network of neurons distributed throughout the brain's inner core. Even when roused from the deepest slumber, there is a subtle yet sublime sensation of being reinserted into the natural flow of time - not so with a knockout blow.}
\par\plain {Not long ago, it seemed to Moto, The Experiment had imploded, sending his capsule into that nauseating spin, frustrating his attempts to secure himself into the jump seat that folded out from the escape capsule\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s wall. He recalled that the capsule was never able to stabilize itself like it was supposed to, because essential things like flight profile and distribution of weight don\u8217\'92t matter when you\u8217\'92re swept up in the cyclonic flow of a supercell storm the size of several mountains.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s an edge-case scenario\u8221\'94, Moto remembered an engineer saying in response to some of his \u8216\'91what-ifs\u8217\'92.}
\par\plain { \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What if one of these detached pods were to descend into a hurricane?\u8221\'94, he had asked.}
