\par\plain {When the pod finally did pop out of the bottom of the icy storm cell and found cleaner air, it was able to quickly right itself.  Moto remembered seeing rain out the window, and a flattening horizon. He remembered fumbling with the harness of his jumpseat.}
\par\plain {Now, suddenly, here he was - curiously splayed out over the capsule\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s cramped quarters, with his face squished against what he suspected to be the floor. He couldn\u8217\'92t be sure of that, because he couldn\u8217\'92t see anything except for jittery, white, electric specks that he knew to be hallucinations incited by the mechanical stimulation of his optic nerve, which meant that flotsam had been knocked loose in his eye\u8217\'92s vitreous sac, and that meant that his head had suffered a vicious blow. This was how Moto concluded he had been knocked out, because he hadn\u8217\'92t yet registered the dull, aching pain emanating from his forehead where some sharp corner had cracked open his skull.}
\par\plain {\tab In the darkness he brought his hand up to his face, and dabbed his fingers gingerly across his brow. There he tested the tender nerves, hoping for a superficial injury, and they stumbled upon a smattering of blood must have had plenty of time to cake.}
\par\plain {I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve been lying here for hours, Moto thought. Maybe days. He had no real way of knowing.}
\par\plain {His fingertips continued to follow the pain up to its source, to the crest of his forehead just under the hairline, where he found that he could pull up a large flap of skin and hair to reveal a cracked bit of skull and even a little hole. As his fingers traced the outline of the cavity, the pain increased, radiating out whenever his fingers dipped down into the gooey wound, sending tendrils of tangy pain round to the back of his head to constrict his skull like a python. }
\par\plain {That action seemed to awaken a soup of screaming nerves in his left shoulder. The pain there was more complete, much sharper, worthy of any oubliette.}
\par\plain {Moto curled up against the chilling darkness, and struggled to maintain a single, clean, conscious thought as the pain threatened to dice the function of his mind piecewise into an incoherent jumble of emotion. Moto knew that  such a fragmented mind is susceptible to sliding down the funnel of despair which sits underneath everyone\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s seat of consciousness. Here he was, crippled, in more pain than he had ever felt, and marooned on an alien planet in a far away galaxy with no hope of rescue. Perhaps if he had known that this was just the beginning, he might not have been able to clamber back up from this mental precipice by convincing himself that he was actually lucky.}
\par\plain {I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92m alive, he reasoned, and Oya is dead.}
\par\plain {He did not spare a thought for Alberto.}
\par\plain {Eventually, he was able to orient himself within the pod, and managed to pull himself into the jumpseat with his good arm. Sinking into the cushion, he tried to invent some goal he could set his mind towards, but unfortunately, this just lead to the realization that the capsule wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t floating comfortably on the ocean\u8217\'92s surface, like it was supposed to. Instead, the absence of light, and warmth, and sound, and movement meant only one thing: his pod was resting comfortably on the bottom of the ocean floor. That darkness outside was not a cloudy night, but likely hundreds of meters of water; enough pressure to pop his lungs if he dared to open the hatch - if he even could.}
\par\plain {Moto sank further into the chair, further into a nihilistic stupor, and he sat like that so long that the sharp spikes of pain in his shoulder began to give way to the slower-moving dull aches that come after, that serve as an unconscious reminder not to move. }
\par\plain {This is, Moto thought, quite literally, rock bottom.}
\par\plain {It wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t the heroic, principled, Moto that emerged from this malaise. Absent the light of hope, the virtuous aspects of his character began to wilt, along the parts of himself that dealt with things like courage, fate, and suicide. In that chilling darkness, it didn\u8217\'92t take long for these affectations of humanity to simply lay down and die, so that the rest of him, the shrewd, practical mammal, could get on to surviving - and if that was impossible, to at least make himself more comfortable.}
\par\plain {He began to grope around blindly with his good right hand for something to wrap around his head, when a tiny green light on the paneling in front of him began to flash. Its light was soft and it beeped irregularly, no doubt signaling some electrical short, but in the relative darkness the thing was blinding. Being the only lightsource, it left much of the cramped pod in a web of splayed, prism shadows, but it illuminated enough surface area to give Moto a disturbing vision of his private hell.}
\par\plain {The first thing he noticed was that the was air cold enough to condense the vapor of his breath into ice. The fact that he had not already sensed this was worrying. Soon his eyes settled on a black fluid that puddled on the floor, and was streaked against the walls, and was even splattered all over his suit. He reached down to touch it, but stopped when he noticed that his hand, too, was drenched in the stuff. Confused, he raised his hand up to the flashing light, turned it over and back, and studied the black fluid\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s wet, specular reflection as it rolled over the contours of his knuckles. }
\par\plain {Blood.}
\par\plain {Red blood absorbing all of the green light so as to appear black, like crude oil. It was everywhere in the strobing darkness, half frozen to whatever surface it had been spattered onto. Moto licked the stuff off the tip of his finger, to make sure, and immediately the familiar iron tang of blood hit his palate. He sighed, then looked round in disbelief at the amount of it plastering the pod\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s walls. It seemed impossible that he could still be alive. }
\par\plain {At least now he had a light to ease his search for something to cover the wound.}
\par\plain {A glint of something sharp caught his eye. It was a piece of the jumpseat\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s harness, an artifact of the broken metal buckle that had shattered when the pod smashed into the water. He picked it up and found that it had enough of an edge to serve as a makeshift blade. In fact it was quite sharp, a near perfect razor, ideally suited for slicing through flesh. His plan was to fashion some kind of to cut a strip of his suit to wrap around his head,  and so he began to saw at his left shoulder where the pain was still greatest, hoping to expose it to the numbing cold.}
\par\plain {Thankfully, it didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t take long for him to make a cylindrical cut all the way around his armpit, but rolling the sleeve down his arm was another matter. The bones that were supposed compose his shoulder had been so thinly splintered that the familiar curves and form of a human arm had vanished. His muscles just stretched like taffy all the way down to his elbow. To make matters worse, a round, bony, and sensitive protrusion nearly poked through the skin about where his tricep should be.}
\par\plain { When he finally did get the springy mass of suit far enough down his arm, was able to unfurl the sleeve and lay it out against the jumpseat\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s armrest. He then made another cut with the intention of creating an elastic band to sit on his head.}
\par\plain {It worked wonderfully. }
\par\plain {A good part of his headache was immediately relieved when the makeshift cap slapped into place. The thing was tight enough to apply an even pressure, so that the crack in his skull did not give and rub against nerves. It almost completely stifled the pain signals that emanated there. It even pressured the great arteries that lined the back of his skull, squelching the blood flow, giving his head an odd sensation of floating, as if it would stand up without his neck doing any work. In this respect, he achieved a certain state of peaceableness, though there was still the matter of his arm. }
\par\plain { He decided to construct a sling. The idea was to get his arm moving in sync with his clavicle, so that the fragments of bone and muscle wouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t grind against nerve with every breath. Fabricating something sturdy enough to do the job was a little more work than he was willing to do, so just cut a slit into his suit near his belly button, into which he pushed his forearm, all the way up to the elbow so that it rested snugly against his stomach. When he tested this contrivance out by sitting up, he found that a lot of the pain did not follow - so long as he didn\u8217\'92t breathe - though breathing was still difficult. Breathing meant the expansion of his lungs to let in air, forcing his chest to move independently of his shoulder, grinding the nerves at the seam. All he could do was close his eyes, grit his teeth, sip the air, and wait for the chill to numb the pain. So that was what he did.}
\par\plain {He used his mind to help the cold along, by imagining it as a curling, glacial mist, seeping into his body through fault lines in the skin, and settling like frost on the membranes of the raw nerves underneath, inhibiting their electrical impulses, their screams for attention. It wouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t take long for the nerves near the skin to freeze over, paving the way for a blue-black chill to creep down into the meat, sucking the needling heat out of his shoulder before continuing on to work its way towards the bone. From there it was frostbite, and it would begin to assault his core where the body heat settles, though that defense would not last long.}
\par\plain {It helped that his head, too, was exposed to the chill. His stream of consciousness began to freeze over, and so time itself seemed to congeal. Through his eyelids, every strobing green flash imprinted itself onto his retina, but his viscous state of mind had difficulty separating them, and so his narrative self started to weave intermittent points in time together as if they were actually sequential events. As more and more sensory stimulation slipped past unrecorded, these glimpses of light grew further and further apart. His unconscious mind began to struggle to manufacture coherence, and it started to invent sensations where there were none: a tickling of his fingers and feet, a deep and droning incorporeal hum that grew louder as the green flashed. The effect moved Moto into a trancelike state, though through it all, his existential self, his I-me-mine, did not completely disappear. In fact, there was enough of him left to sense his own impending doom, the stretching of time, the thinness of his life. Starting with the ever-slowing cosmic tick of the universe, he could extrapolate out, and understood that it would eventually stop ticking completely. At that point, time would freeze completely into a kind of reflective prism, crystallizing around whatever his last twinkling thought might be, and that would be death. }
\par\plain {As his mind crept towards this jeweled stasis, its even keel was disturbed by a brief, yearning protestation to stay alert, so that he might revel in the experience of dying for as long as possible, so that his last transcendent moment might be one worthy of eternity - if indeed that was how it worked. }
\par\plain {But he did not die. He just sat there in the blinking darkness for another hour more - an empty husk, not aware enough to understand that he was still alive. }
\par\plain {Then there was  a rumbling, a fumbling. Then a sudden, disruptive shift in his equilibrium. Moto\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyelids slid open quickly enough to catch a glimpse of a bright beam of white light as it raked across the interior of the pod, looking just like an errant ray of god\u8217\'92s divine light .}
\par\plain {So, it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s true.}
\par\plain {The light disappeared almost as soon as it came, and as it left, Moto\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s aches and pains returned, and then he understood that he was not yet dead. It was almost depressing, but next came the realization that there was something outside. Something with a light source. Even more, gravity was now pulling in a different direction: the back of his jumpseat was now \u8216\'91down\u8217\'92, the opposite wall was \u8216\'91up\u8217\'92, and the floor was \u8216\'91forwards\u8217\'92. There was a sense of motion.}
\par\plain {Something is taking me somewhere.}
\par\plain {He rolled over onto his side and pulled himself up towards the thin window. The blackness outside was as deep as space, and he felt a familiar feeling as he peered out into the abyss, like he was looking out of one of The Experiment\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s windows, only instead of stars there was a galaxy of particulate matter, illuminated by some out of sight white light, and scrolling past the window like a tilt-shifted Milky Way. Some of the bits glinted so brightly, it seemed as they were little shards of glass, or microscopic diamonds.}
\par\plain {It then occurred to Moto, in a realization as violent and unwelcome as being birthed, that the little bits might be silt and sand, that the pod might just be floating there in some deep, arctic basin, and that the rushing water outside might be part of some global conveyor belt, not unlike the engine that drives the earth\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s climate. }
\par\plain {He strained to get a better look, half expecting to be able pick apart the composition of the silt, half expecting to get a glimpse of some noodly or mechanical appendage to get a sense whatever was carrying him, if indeed he was being carried. His efforts to accomplish either were frustrated by a fog that had begun to build up on the glass.}
\par\plain {Moto reached down to wipe the condensation away, but it did not come off. At first he thought that there might be two glass panes, and that humid air had somehow snuk in-between them. After inspecting the cloudy film more closely, he could see that it was actually a pale buildup of gunk on the outside of the glass, and the stuff quickly began to accumulate into little phlegm-like globs at the edges where the glass joined its metal frame. Soon a faint cloud of the stuff began to spread across the whole of the pane, and then it became so opaque that Moto could no longer see clearly out of it. Instead of fine specks of particulate matter, there  was a twinkling blur, appearing against the diffusely lit glass like a stream of light and smoke. It was as if he had taken another cosmic step out, so that instead of a miniature galaxy scrolling past, there shone an arm of the universe, a cloudy ribbon of galaxies.}
\par\plain {Moto tried to work out exactly what the gunk sticking to the glass might be, and all his figuring missed the mark. Ehile there were indeed bits of rock and carbonate mixed in with the floating detritus, what glued the rest of the particulate matter to the glass was electricity, the Van der Waals force, the fundamental attraction of opposite charges, the organizing engine of organic molecules, and therefore, of life itself. The sticky substance that now obscured his vision was a conglomerate of living cells, and Moto didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t begin to suspect it until a multitude of tiny black dots began to appear in the cloudy film. }
\par\plain {It was obvious that these black dots weren\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t things themselves, they were just spots of clean glass, clearly rendering the deep blackness of the ocean outside.  As he looked closer, he could see that these empty spaces were growing, slowly and radially outward. }
\par\plain {The expansion of each pinprick of blackness was easy to see, so heavily contrasted against the soft white glow. Moto lowered his head even closer to the glass to study a single spot that grew more quickly than the others. It grew and grew until it reached the diameter of his pinky\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s tip, at which point it\u8217\'92s growth slowed, then stopped. Then its edges began to wobble, crack, before morphing into a fringe of branching ringlets which, after a sudden shiver, exploded outwards in a quick fractal burst - appearing out of the ether like a footprint of a snowflake set against the cloudy film. Then another nearby spot followed suit, its edges exploding outwards with nearly the same procedural, branching symmetry, its tendrils seeking out and swallowing the gunk that had defined the previous star\u8217\'92s shape. Then another phlegm-free spot burst outwards, and another, and another, when finally a multitude of the little geometric eruptions seemed to pop all at once, sweeping over the glass, clearing it up in the amount of time it took for Moto to gasp incredulously at the astonishing sight.}
\par\plain {Beautiful\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85}
\par\plain {Moto considered it.}
\par\plain {Most likely likely a chemical reaction, he thought, but there was an undeniable liveliness to it.  A sense of ordered complexity. Maybe something small was eating something even smaller. Maybe it was alien life.}
\par\plain {He didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t have to stew long before he got an answer to his question, because almost as soon as the glass was cleared up, his pod was plunged into a horde of thin, white, gelatinous tubes, looking something like transparent tapeworms, all swept up in the rushing current, and twitching back and forth like headless snakes.}
\par\plain {Hundreds of them washed up against the glass, only breifly so that Moto couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t study their furious wriggling body. One of them did get stuck, and Moto could see that it was a most primitive organism, just a colony of cells latticed together to form a tube, with some plasmodic fluid encased within, sloshing around with each nervous tick. Maybe the fluid inside was a way of sharing nutrients, of sharing proteins, amino acids, or vitamins, between the cells. Whatever the case, this basic design typified the type of all the other, smaller organisms that Moto began to notice; all clear vesicles holding a fluid. Little pyramids, diamonds, horseshoes, asymmetrical blobs, spiniferus spheres, and everything in between; a menagerie of morphological variety, unrivaled by even earth\u8217\'92s prokaryotic kingdom.}
\par\plain {\tab Almost as quickly as it came, the herd of jelly-like creatures began to thin, revealing, like a curtain drawn, a light-show that had begun to sparkle in the darkness beneath. Here and there, dim, red-orange lights flashed, flickered, then faded, looking like the bioluminescent effulgence secreted from the glands of squid or minnows, only much, much larger. For a brief moment, Moto\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s mind conjured up images of the jurassic age, of evolutionary experiments: creatures with mounds of teeth, whale-sized, larger even, but as his mind\u8217\'92s unhinged imagination churned, it became clear that the lights weren\u8217\'92t biological, but geological. Far below an infant underwater mountainside was growing. The bright spurts of red were just outflows of volcanic mush, their tendrils quickly curdling into igneous rock. }
\par\plain {\tab It all looked familiar. Earth-like.}
\par\plain {Maybe, Moto thought, Earth-like just means life-like. }
\par\plain {The volcanic slope continued to rise, softly, then steeply, then suddenly it plummeted back down into the abyss, perhaps a continental cleft in the ocean rock. Then the mountainside rushed back up, and his pod, still carried along by some unknown force, flew into an empty magmatic chute carved out of the escarpment. }
\par\plain {All at once, the world outside became clear as the white lights of his escort craft lit up the rocky tube. Against the dark rock, white crystal chimneys funneled hydrothermal gases out into the water, their heat distorting Moto\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s view of the glistening calcium leaves that formed in the wake. Streaks of glittering gold flashed in the walls, spiralling through the tube wherever sulfide had reacted with methane to form pyrite. Here, too, a galaxy of white, gelatinous forms thrived, taking advantage of the unique chemistry. Spindly gelatinous bags clung to the walls, filter feeding, and things that looked like familiar snow white fronds of coral, meters wide, lilting in the chute\u8217\'92s speedy current. }
\par\plain {It soon became clear that the tube was part of some larger underground network, designed by intelligence, not happenstance. Eventually his escort took one of its many forks, one that shot vertically upwards, and the change in direction sent Moto into an all too familiar tumble. Thankfully, he was able to catch himself with his feet, and stood, able to look out the ring of glass near the pod\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s hatch to observe changing ecology. The walls of this shaft were dominated by sprawling cobweb communities, draping over sharp black rock like lace doilies. The complexities of their patterns reflected the changing pressure and content of the water column, becoming more dense, more intricate as the pod was pulled further up. Though the milky webs looked so delicate, they were sturdy enough to withstand his escort\u8217\'92s draft. }
\par\plain {After a few minutes of this, all trace of the webs had completely disappeared, and the seawater began to transform into a thicker, greener, organic solution. Visibility dropped to just a few inches, or none at all wherever the glass had, once again, become clogged with little living things. Eventually it dawned on Moto that he must be heading towards the surface. Then came the realization that he was, truly, still alive.}
\par\plain {When his pod broke the surface, the green goo sloughed off the window, and he could see that he was in a small cave that was being illuminated by a ring of fluorescent tubes attached to the ceiling, just a few meters above. The craft that had carried him along was floating next to him. It was bright orange, and structurally no different than the deep water submersibles back on earth; just a metal box frame sheathed in a hydrodynamic foil, with two jet propulsion systems jutting out at the sides. Suspended inside it all was a glass ball. Sitting inside of that was pale, scrawny, human being. Behind the green blur, that was all he could make out, but it was unmistakably human , with short hair on a large head, arms, torso, legs, even breasts. It was a naked woman. She exited her submersible, and clambered barefoot onto the top of Moto\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s pod. }
\par\plain {He heard a fumbling at the hatch, and then the pitter-patter of the woman\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s feet as she shuffled around, trying to get a better grip. At first she was only able to loosen the seal enough to let in an acrid smell, close to rotten eggs, as if the pod had been drenched in sulfuric acid, though that wasn\u8217\'92t enough to prepare Moto for the off putting sight of the woman when she opened the hatch. }
\par\plain {Though technically applicable, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91young woman\u8217\'92 was hardly the right term to describe her. She was young in age only. Woman in sex only. Her genetic code had drifted so far from youthful vigor and feminine form, that she looked like a different creature altogether. Her head drooped low and forwards with the most serious case of scholar\u8217\'92s neck that Moto had ever seen. Some curious spinal deformity; it was what caused her movements to seem unnatural. Her collarbones seemed to be pointed the wrong way, so that her shoulders rose up level with her chin, and yet her arms still seemed too long, like she could touch her knees from a resting position, though Moto suspected she wouldn't be able to hold on for long, because there was hardly any muscle on the bone. It was a miracle she had managed to open the hatch. Moto might have taken her for an alien if it weren\u8217\'92t for the fact that she}
\par\plain {spoke clear and precise english.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What took you so long!\u8221\'94 she shrieked. Her voice grated as if her throat had been shredded by decades of cigarette smoke.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I, uh\u8230\'85.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yeah, no shit.\u8221\'94 She was eying the blood caked to the walls of the pod. \u8220\'93There\u8217\'92ll be time for stories later. Out you get.\u8221\'94 The spidery woman then jumped off the pod and onto the wet, slimy rock next to it, clearly expecting Moto to climb up and out on his own, as if she didn\u8217\'92t  notice the look of utter exhaustion in his eyes, or expect his busted arm to hinder him,. She shot his pod an annoyed look when he didn\u8217\'92t immediately spring up after her.}
\par\plain {Not wanting to upset the creature, Moto balanced himself tip-toe on the head of the pod\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s jumpseat, so that his shoulders rose above the hatch\u8217\'92s opening. With great effort he was able to press the full weight of his body high enough out of the hole so that he could twist his butt around to sit on the hatch\u8217\'92s rim. He then swung his weak, tingling legs over through and out to drape over the pod\u8217\'92s sloped, slimy side, before doubling over in pain.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What the hell is wrong with you?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Could you help me down?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Moto reached out to her, clearly requesting a steady hand. }
\par\plain {As the woman\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes read through the obligation writ out by Moto\u8217\'92s beggared posture, her expression shifted slightly from irritation to confusion. She took in a quick, fluttered breath, as if preparing a question, but evidently she thought better of it. Instead, she reached up with her hand, but not to help Moto down. Only her spiny index finger was extended. }
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {Her finger was shaking, and when it finally touched his skin, she looked back up at him, eyes now wide under knitted brows, looking every bit like a crazed, soothsaying hermit.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh SHIT!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Immediatelthen took off running around the pod, screaming obscenities, heading for the dark tunnel on the other side of the cave. She moved moved too quickly across the algae covered rock, and so her plant foot slipped when she tried to dart into the small hole. Her foot skidded through the soft green fungus like a crashing meteor, and she fell hard onto the ground, hip first, causing her head to whip against the fuzzy rock. A cringe-inducing crack echoed briefly through the small cave, and crimson blood leapt from her head to stain the algae. She did not get up.}
\par\plain {Moto clambered down after her, careful not to make the same mistake. By the time he got to her corpse, a thick and vibrant yellow fluid, looking something like a pureed banana peel, begin to stream out of her nose. It trickled out of her tear ducts too, puddling up in her eye sockets before streaming down her cheek and onto the algal mat. }
\par\plain {Moto kneeled in stunned silence as he watched the substance begin to flow, slowly, uphill. Eventually it reached the cave wall, but instead of pushing along the edge, it began to climb up, weaving through algae like a vine in search of sunlight. Moto reached out a curious finger. When it was inches away, the substance responded in kind, sending out a thin, wriggling tendril, testing the air, as if seeking out the source of the new scent. Moto recoiled, and so did the viscous stem, but instead of continuing on up the wall, it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s began to move back down. It moved slowly at first, but soon picked up momentum, and nearly began to roll towards him, shooting out little gooey harpoons towards Moto\u8217\'92s bare feet. }
\par\plain {Moto quickly stepped backwards into the tunnel and off of the green carpet of algae, but he still nearly slipped, because the rocky surface inside was coated with a clear, jelly-like substance. The cold, clear goo squeezed through the spaces in between his toes. It felt like alcoholic sanitizer, but Moto feared the opposite, because it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s putrid smell was overwhelming. }
\par\plain { He looked down at his feet and began to imagine little alien lifeforms living in the gel that could penetrate his skin. He supposed he would have felt it by now: a slight tickle as the bacterium began to burrow. Whatever the stuff was, the probing yellow fluid outside wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t willing to wade into it.}
\par\plain {Moto tried to spit out the smell. It tangible, like a cloud of dust floating in the air.}
\par\plain {Everythings wrong. }
\par\plain {He didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t like what he saw, what he smelt, what he felt. Only his ears had been spared nausea. The only sound was an electric hum, emanating somewhere deep within the cavern behind him. That was enough to convince him to delve further into the mucous-membraned throat of this alien world.}
\par\plain {\tab His step was unsteady, and he was forced to brace himself against the low ceiling with his good shoulder. As he scraped through the tunnel, gel sloughed off the rock, and long strings of it dripped like saliva down his back. Absent sight, his mind invented the most disturbing visions of a milk-green, feculent sludge oozing out of the cracks between his fingers every time his hand planted in the ground, or against the wall, popping little snot balls that grew out of the rock\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s pores.}
\par\plain {\tab Eventually his eye caught a faint, pinkish light that sparkled like fire off of the wet rock ahead. He moved closer, and the cave walls narrowed. Further ahead, the air grew thick, condensing into a glowing, pink wall of mist that pulsed in and out of a seemingly incandescent cave, its movement synced to the gently arcing sine wave of the now sonorous hum. }
\par\plain {Moto plunged his hand into it, and his skin prickled. Then he closed his eyes and stepped into it, let the sound and mist wash over him, and he found that he could breathe cleanly. There was a dusty feeling that scratched the back of his throat, but in other respects he felt rejuvenated. The pain his shoulder subsided, and his brain no longer felt like brick suspended by wires that were bolted to the inside of his skull. Encouraged, he opened his eyes, and stepped into the softly glowing grotto.}
\par\plain {It was a relatively small cave, about fifteen meters in diameter, and its floor, walls, and ceiling were black and spongy. Planted in the pores of this structure were soft-red aqueous sacs, ovular, some large and sticking out of the ground, or hanging down from above like ripe fruit about to fall. Some were small, the size of a pebble, littering the floor like salmon eggs ready to be fertilized.}
\par\plain {Moto picked up one of the tiniest and squished it between his fingers. A large amount of red, watery juice streamed out, and all that was left in his hand was the thin, transparent skin. These weren\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t the same snot-balls that he had squished further back. He moved to one of the large ones to inspect further.}
\par\plain {This largest sac, about half a meter long, was implanted into the wall and seemed to be illuminated from within. It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s skin was less transparent, but there was enough of a shadow for him to see that there was something inside of it. }
\par\plain {So, he touched it. }
\par\plain {Then he poked it, and it wobbled.}
\par\plain {He gave it a gentle tap, and this time, as his fingers brushed against the skin, they wiped away the foggy layer of condensation, allowing him to see a little bit more of what was inside.}
\par\plain {An embryo. Some kind of egg.}
\par\plain {Moto knew it wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t exactly an egg; there was no shell, but it wasn\u8217\'92t quite like a womb, either. Whatever grew inside was just floating, unattached. }
\par\plain {He tried to get a better look at the little alien growing inside by brushing away more of the cloudy film, but he was careless. The sac\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s skin was so thin that the brush of his fingernail\u8217\'92s edge was enough to cut it open. The laceration was just a millimeter across, but the skin was so fragile that the weight of the contents inside ripped it wider, and it all spilled out onto the floor with a horrific, wet smack. }
\par\plain {There on the floor, blue and purple, already dead, probably never alive, was a perfectly human baby.}
\par\plain {It was the most intense thing he\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d ever seen.}
\par\plain {If only I had a camera.}
